Six works in the corpus discuss the nature of legitimate evidence in legal disputes, all from the Sanskrit Dharmaśāstra tradition. The **Kātyāyana Smṛti** (ch. 24–27) gives the most systematic treatment, defining proof as divine (ordeals) or human (document, witnesses, possession) and ranking their relative strength. The **Bṛhaspati Smṛti** (ch. 1) covers burden of proof and the king as last-resort evidence. The **Nāradasmṛti** (ch. 1), **Manusmṛti** (ch. 8), **Yājñavalkya Smṛti** (ch. 2), and **Yama Smṛti** (ch. 1) each treat witness qualifications, valid documents, and categories of inadmissible testimony.
